# ADR-0010 — Tool Execution Model

- Status: Accepted
- Date: 2026-07-19
- Deciders: Pharos Architecture Team

---

# Context

The Runtime is designed to execute user intent.

Many intents require interaction with external systems.

Examples include:

- reading files
- searching knowledge
- sending email
- creating calendar events
- calling APIs
- executing shell commands
- interacting with databases
- browsing the web

Embedding these capabilities directly into RuntimeEngine,
RuntimePlanner or Workflow would tightly couple the Runtime to specific
implementations and make testing difficult.

The Runtime therefore requires a dedicated Tool abstraction.

---

# Decision

All external capabilities shall be represented as Runtime Tools.

The Runtime itself never performs external work directly.

Instead, Workflows invoke Tool contracts.

```
RuntimeIntent
        │
        ▼
RuntimePlanner
        │
        ▼
RuntimePlan
        │
        ▼
WorkflowBuilder
        │
        ▼
Workflow
        │
        ▼
Tool
        │
        ▼
External System
```

The Runtime is responsible for orchestration.

Tools are responsible for integration.

---

# Tool Responsibilities

A Tool represents one executable capability.

Examples:

- ReadFileTool
- SearchKnowledgeTool
- SendEmailTool
- CalendarTool
- HttpTool
- GitTool
- DatabaseTool

Each Tool owns only one capability.

---

# Tool Contract

Every Tool shall expose a common interface.

Conceptually:

```text
execute(input)

↓

ToolResult
```

The Runtime never depends on concrete Tool implementations.

---

# Tool Registry

Tool discovery is delegated to ToolRegistry.

The Runtime never constructs tools directly.

```
Workflow

↓

ToolRegistry

↓

Tool
```

ToolRegistry is responsible for:

- registration
- lookup
- availability
- dependency injection

---

# Runtime Responsibilities

The Runtime:

- selects work
- builds workflows
- coordinates execution

The Runtime never:

- sends HTTP directly
- reads files directly
- accesses databases directly
- invokes external APIs directly

Those responsibilities belong to Tools.

---

# Dependency Rules

Workflow depends only on Tool contracts.

Tool implementations never depend on RuntimeEngine.

RuntimePlanner never depends on Tool implementations.

RuntimePlan contains no Tool instances.

---

# Tool Independence

Tools are independent modules.

Removing one Tool must not affect the Runtime.

Adding a new Tool requires no Runtime modification.

---

# Error Handling

Tool failures are reported through ToolResult.

The Runtime decides how to react.

Tools never decide Runtime behaviour.

---

# Security

Tools are the Runtime's security boundary.

Permissions, validation and external access policies belong to Tool
implementations.

The Runtime assumes Tools enforce their own operational constraints.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Runtime executes integrations directly

Rejected.

This tightly couples orchestration to infrastructure.

---

## Planner invokes Tools

Rejected.

Planning should remain deterministic and side-effect free.

---

## RuntimePlan stores Tool instances

Rejected.

RuntimePlan is data only.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- modular integrations
- provider independence
- isolated testing
- replaceable implementations
- clear security boundary

Negative:

- one additional abstraction
- ToolRegistry becomes required infrastructure

The architectural benefits outweigh the additional complexity.

---

# Future Evolution

Future Runtime versions may support:

- dynamic Tool loading
- remote Tools
- MCP-compatible Tools
- permission-aware Tools
- Tool capability discovery
- Tool version negotiation
- sandboxed execution
- distributed Tool execution

None of these extensions require changes to RuntimeEngine.

